# Context Engineering

Follow `docs/policy/context-engineering-policy.md` for the full guide. Key principles summarized here.

## Core Principles

- **Minimize tokens**: Find the smallest set of high-signal tokens that maximize outcomes.
- **Right altitude**: Balance brittle (prescriptive steps) vs. vague (generic guidance). Calibration test: would a senior engineer need this detail?
- **Single source of truth**: Tool description = HOW; system prompt = WHEN. Never explain the same concept twice.
- **Examples over rules**: One comprehensive example > three paragraphs of explanation.
- **Trust model capability**: If a competent developer wouldn't need the instruction, the model doesn't either.

## System Prompts

- Structure with XML tags or Markdown headers for distinct sections.
- Reference tools by name, don't re-explain their parameters.
- Compress prescriptive lists into terse sentences.
- Use professional, terse language -- cut filler and defensive repetition.

## Tool Descriptions

```typescript
description: `[One-line purpose]
[When to use - 2-3 bullets max]
[Key behavior - only if non-obvious]`
```

Target under 150 words. Let Zod schemas self-document parameters.

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Fix |
|---|---|
| Tool explained in prompt AND description | Keep in description only |
| Multiple similar code examples | One canonical example |
| "1. Analyze 2. Understand 3. Fix" | "Fix incrementally, verify after" |
| "CRITICAL: You MUST always..." | State once |
| All 50 tool definitions in every request | Dynamic discovery |
| Full conversation history forever | Sliding windows + summarization |

## Audit Checklist

- [ ] Is this explained elsewhere? Consolidate.
- [ ] Would a senior dev need this? Remove if obvious.
- [ ] Can this be an example instead?
- [ ] Are there prescriptive lists? Compress.
- [ ] Does this duplicate tool docs? Remove from prompt.
